  "text": "We first evaluated the performance in deconvolving epigenetic data, clustering cells, and inferring GRNs using data simulated from the Symphony model. We simulated data for n = 100 cells in K = 3 clusters with d ranging from 5 to 20 genes and l = 50 using the Symphony model. Figure 5 (a) shows scatterplots of deconvolved peak heights (p p p k ) compared to actual data. We compared the performance of Symphony to two other deconvolution methods: deconf [CITATION_1] which uses NMF, and Dsection (Erkkilä et al., 2010) which is based on a Bayesian model. While Dsection captures only the largest cluster, deconf underestimates the cluster-specific peak heights. The behavior of Dsection was reproducible across simulations, and is likely due to the lack of identifiability in the model for epigenetic data alone, as discussed above. as an example, compared to the actual R k , confirming the ability of Symphony in inferring GRNs.",
